  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_0' aria-label=\" Tahir V. Isani versus Madan Waman Chodankar, (Since Deceased) Now Through His Legal Representatives & Ors. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('0','2025','2025_5_2810_2826','2025INSC1044'); ><font size='4'> <strong>TAHIR V. ISANI<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>MADAN WAMAN CHODANKAR, (SINCE DECEASED) NOW THROUGH HIS LEGAL REPRESENTATIVES & ORS. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 5 S.C.R. 2810</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 1044</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010008472025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : VIKRAM NATH, SANDEEP MEHTA</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Whether the High Court was justified in holding that since the appellant was a transferee pendent lite of judgment debtor, therefore, in view of provisions of Rule 102 of Or.XXI of CPC, the application filed by the appellant under of Or.XXI CPC was not maintainable. Headnotes&dagger; Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 &ndash; Or.XXI, RR.97, 98, 99, 100, 101, 102 &ndash; In 1996, respondent no.1-tenant filed a special civil suit no.97/1996/B against MK for dissolution of partnership, recovery of profit and ejectment &ndash; No<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 06-05-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 6391/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('0','2025','2025_5_2810_2826','2025INSC1044','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-